on top of our Jamaican
indigenous music,

21:02.552 --> 21:07.181
such as mento, calypso, Kumina.

21:07.349 --> 21:09.141
♪ Simmer down ♪

21:09.309 --> 21:10.768
♪ You lickin' too hot ♪

21:10.936 --> 21:12.979
♪ So simmer down ♪

21:13.146 --> 21:14.480
♪ Soon you'll get dropped... ♪

21:14.648 --> 21:19.402
We were at a bar one evening
and one of the guys,

21:19.569 --> 21:21.821
them says to us,
"Listen to this group."

21:21.989 --> 21:23.906
And they punched the jukebox

21:24.074 --> 21:27.827
and the song was called
"Simmer Down."

21:27.995 --> 21:30.788
And no more other tune
play on that box

21:30.956 --> 21:32.373
the whole time we were there

21:32.541 --> 21:34.208
but "Simmer Down," I tell you.

21:34.376 --> 21:38.337
- ♪ Oh, simmer down ♪
- ♪ Oh, control your temper ♪

21:38.505 --> 21:41.841
- ♪ Simmer down ♪
- ♪ For the battle will be hotter... ♪

21:42.009 --> 21:45.094
Livingston: "Simmer Down" went straight
into the number-one position,

21:45.262 --> 21:47.221
and the Wailers were launched.

21:47.389 --> 21:49.932
♪ Oh, that I'm leaving
you today ♪

21:50.100 --> 21:52.101
♪ Simmer down... ♪

21:54.146 --> 21:55.813
Interviewer:
What was it like working at Studio 1,

21:55.981 --> 21:57.231
where you started,
in those days?

21:57.399 --> 21:58.691
Bob:
Yeah, it was good, you know,

21:58.859 --> 22:01.736
'cause my first experience
within music,

22:01.903 --> 22:03.654
working with
some good musicians

22:03.822 --> 22:05.698
and trying to get
the harmonies and everything...

22:05.866 --> 22:07.408
- it was great.
- Interviewer: l heard you actually...

22:07.576 --> 22:09.285
you personally
lived in the studio.

22:09.453 --> 22:10.870
( Bob laughs ) Sometime.

22:11.038 --> 22:12.788
Interviewer: Coxsone made you
a room out the back.

22:12.956 --> 22:14.749
( Bob chuckling ) Yes.

22:14.916 --> 22:17.877
McDonald:
Well, Coxsone was a smart guy

22:18.045 --> 22:21.255
in that he has an ear
for music, good music.

22:21.423 --> 22:23.090
He might not have been
an instrument player.

22:23.258 --> 22:25.509
He might not even know
if the guitar is tuned,

22:25.677 --> 22:28.971
but he knows when
the sound is right.

22:29.139 --> 22:31.182
He has his own program
on the radio,

22:31.350 --> 22:32.725
his own record shop.

22:32.893 --> 22:35.686
Has his own sound system,
has his own studio.

22:35.854 --> 22:37.396
So he's obviously a leader.

22:37.564 --> 22:39.440
Coxsone was like a father
to us, you know,

22:39.608 --> 22:40.900
to be honest with you.

22:41.068 --> 22:42.401
Coxsone was like
a father to us.

22:42.569 --> 22:44.570
He cared for us.

22:48.742 --> 22:50.743
Sibley:
Coxsone gave Robbie a little room

22:50.911 --> 22:52.912
around the back
of the premises.

22:53.080 --> 22:54.914
I didn't have anywhere
to live neither.

22:55.082 --> 22:57.666
So Robbie and me lived there.
Both of us lived there.

22:57.834 --> 23:00.544
So we became intimate,
good friends.

23:00.712 --> 23:03.005
He gave Robbie a record player

23:03.173 --> 23:06.300
and a lot of foreign records.

23:06.468 --> 23:08.886
Robbie was a fanatic
in listening to these people

23:09.054 --> 23:11.555
because he was a serious,
focused man,

23:11.723 --> 23:13.808
even as a youth.

23:13.975 --> 23:19.438
Jamaican music developed
from what we call do-overs,

23:19.606 --> 23:22.608
a version of somebody's
song in America.

23:23.610 --> 23:25.986
♪ Each night l ask ♪

23:26.154 --> 23:29.865
♪ The stars up above ♪

23:30.033 --> 23:35.830
♪ Why must l be
a teenager in love? ♪

23:35.997 --> 23:39.458
♪ Put me in your
milling machine ♪

23:39.626 --> 23:43.546
♪ I never thought
you could act so mean ♪

23:43.713 --> 23:47.716
♪ Now I'm wondering
what to do ♪

23:47.884 --> 23:51.679
♪ To see if you could
love me, too... ♪

23:51.847 --> 23:54.974
McDonald: Bob Marley had a good sound
'cause he's singing lead

23:55.142 --> 23:56.475
and the harmony was tight.

23:56.643 --> 24:00.312
The harmony Bunny carried,
and Peter was fantastic.

24:01.606 --> 24:06.652
♪ Why must l be a teenager ♪

24:06.820 --> 24:09.238
♪ In love? ♪

24:09.406 --> 24:13.701
Rita: Peter and Bunny was
the most vocal one to say hi,

24:13.869 --> 24:18.330
but Bob was very reserved
and just look.

24:18.498 --> 24:20.249
As you would say,
just "cotch and look."

24:21.960 --> 24:23.335
Andy:
Well, as much as there was

24:23.503 --> 24:25.671
this obvious
love and admiration

24:25.839 --> 24:27.798
for each other
and of each other,

24:27.966 --> 24:30.801
there was always a deep,
underlying tension

24:30.969 --> 24:34.263
that none would be
a "yes man" to the other.

24:35.682 --> 24:39.518
I think the music was the glue
that held them together.

24:39.686 --> 24:49.820
♪ Feel them spirit ♪

24:51.031 --> 24:57.369
♪ Lord, l thank you ♪

24:58.663 --> 25:01.874
♪ I'm gonna put it on ♪

25:02.042 --> 25:03.626
♪ I'm gonna put it on... ♪

25:12.636 --> 25:15.721
By then he was admiring me.

25:19.100 --> 25:21.435
I got a letter from Bunny,
bringing a letter.

25:21.603 --> 25:25.231
It was him sending his letter
through his friend, not by himself.

25:25.398 --> 25:29.068
And to say, yes, he likes me
and want to talk to me.

25:29.236 --> 25:31.153
I say, "Come over and talk."

25:31.321 --> 25:34.198
And he would stay
on the other side of the road and...

25:34.366 --> 25:37.826
he was very shy. He was very shy.
He was a shy guy.

25:37.994 --> 25:43.415
♪ I'll play your
favorite song, darling... ♪

25:43.583 --> 25:45.167
Rita: He had a seriousness,

25:45.335 --> 25:48.963
and he was one that you could say
was reaching out for love.

25:50.090 --> 25:53.259
( Sibley speaking )

25:56.930 --> 25:59.640
l didn't think l liked
brown-skin men.

25:59.808 --> 26:04.603
L always dream of a guy...
tall, black, handsome.

26:04.771 --> 26:08.315
Every young girl's dream in Jamaica
is to have a tall, black boyfriend.

26:10.151 --> 26:12.027
They would call Bob an outcast

26:12.195 --> 26:14.613
because he really don't belong to no...
you're in between.

26:14.781 --> 26:16.156
You're black and white,
so they're...

26:16.324 --> 26:17.825
( tsks )
"You're not even black."

26:19.619 --> 26:21.870
Danny Sims:
I think he always felt like an outsider

26:22.038 --> 26:24.373
because he was a half-breed.

26:24.541 --> 26:27.126
And when Mortimer Planno
took him in,

26:27.294 --> 26:30.713
well, that automatically
gave him acceptance.

26:32.340 --> 26:35.509
Sibley: Mortimer Planno was
a Rasta spiritual leader

26:35.677 --> 26:37.469
who taught Bob.

26:37.637 --> 26:39.179
Danny: He was like a preacher.

26:39.347 --> 26:43.142
He preached Rastafarianism
and he had a following.

26:43.310 --> 26:47.938
( Singing )

26:48.106 --> 26:51.317
Danny: He hooked up with Bob
as a young boy.

26:51.484 --> 26:53.694
I think that
they gelled together.

26:53.862 --> 26:56.739
- Interviewer: Bob looked up to him?
- Oh, yes.

26:57.741 --> 27:00.159
( Sibley speaking )

27:25.435 --> 27:27.311
Allan "Skill" Cole:
The Rastafarian were the only

27:27.479 --> 27:30.898
true Afrocentric black people

27:31.066 --> 27:34.276
who preached self-reliance,
who preached self-confidence.

27:35.862 --> 27:38.447
McDonald: But we interpret
the Bible a different way.

27:38.615 --> 27:40.658
Most of these places that they're
telling you about

27:40.825 --> 27:42.242
in the Bible is in Africa.

27:42.410 --> 27:44.912
The Garden of Eden
is in Africa.

27:45.080 --> 27:48.123
The teaching that we get
from the elders, then,

27:48.291 --> 27:51.794
is that we always have to look
to a black man as God

27:51.961 --> 27:55.631
for we, somebody that
we can identiry with.

27:56.633 --> 27:58.550
( Bob speaking )

28:15.860 --> 28:17.236
McDonald:
Emperor Haile Selassie l

28:17.404 --> 28:21.073
is the reincarnation
of Jesus Christ.

28:21.241 --> 28:24.827
He is our God, Rasta God.

28:24.994 --> 28:28.914
Rasta said the purpose
of life is to be happy.

28:29.082 --> 28:31.583
Everybody's
supposed to be happy

28:31.751 --> 28:34.420
and live in peace,
love and unity.

28:34.587 --> 28:36.088
Yeah, man.

28:38.091 --> 28:40.884
I think when him start take it
serious now as a Rastaman

28:41.052 --> 28:44.221
was when him start
growing dreadlocks.

28:44.389 --> 28:47.266
Cindy Breakspeare: Locks meant
that you were a Rastafarian

28:47.434 --> 28:49.727
and you've taken a vow...
Nazarite vow...

28:49.894 --> 28:52.271
not to cut or comb your hair
for a certain length of time,

28:52.439 --> 28:55.774
and it has a significance
and is not to be taken lightly.

28:55.942 --> 28:57.943
How important
are the dreadlocks?

28:58.111 --> 28:59.445
This? This is my identity, man.

28:59.612 --> 29:01.530
Is that part of being a Rasta?

29:01.698 --> 29:03.282
Yeah, this is my identity.

29:03.450 --> 29:07.578
Then you go through
all the various rules

29:07.746 --> 29:09.913
for living as set out
by the Bible...

29:10.081 --> 29:13.751
how you eat, how you live,
how you treat other people.

29:13.918 --> 29:16.795
And he believed that if you practice
these things,

29:16.963 --> 29:18.380
well, life will be better...

29:18.548 --> 29:20.632
not only for you,
but for everyone else.

29:20.800 --> 29:34.188
♪ Got to have kaya now ♪

29:34.355 --> 29:37.399
♪ For the rain is falling... ♪

29:37.567 --> 29:39.860
Reporter:
Marijuana is illegal in Jamaica,

29:40.028 --> 29:43.614
but the Rastas say they smoke it because
the Bible tells them to.

29:43.782 --> 29:48.494
The "Book of Revelation" says
to "partake of the herb."

29:48.661 --> 29:51.622
The herb was like
a sacramental food to us.

29:51.790 --> 29:56.376
We take it for reasons,
not just to get high.

29:56.544 --> 29:59.671
It put us in a holy,
peaceful, happy,

29:59.839 --> 30:02.424
inspirational mood.

30:02.592 --> 30:04.968
Interviewer:
Were you born as a Rasta?

30:05.136 --> 30:07.846
When I was born,
you know, and growing,

30:08.014 --> 30:12.017
there was a certain amount
of consciousness

30:12.185 --> 30:14.144
in the higher self

30:14.312 --> 30:16.688
that, you know,

30:16.856 --> 30:18.398
it was always a lonely world,

30:18.566 --> 30:23.403
not finding people who might
think like me, you know?

30:23.571 --> 30:25.739
So off I'm going, I'm going on,

30:25.907 --> 30:28.700
I come to Kingston,
meet some more people.

30:28.868 --> 30:30.494
Them people is Rasta.

30:30.662 --> 30:34.540
It's after that l find out
it's the same thing l have inside.

30:34.707 --> 30:35.958
It's the same thing.

30:36.125 --> 30:37.835
How old were you when
this started to happen?

30:38.002 --> 30:41.421
- This is about 17, 18, you know?
- Ah.

30:41.589 --> 30:45.759
I think in the belief
or knowledge

30:45.927 --> 30:51.723
of Haile Selassie,
Bob found his real father...

30:52.767 --> 30:55.102
which he had never really knew.

30:55.270 --> 30:57.187
I think he saw himself now.

30:57.355 --> 30:59.273
This is where
he found himself, yes.

30:59.440 --> 31:02.067
No more about being
half white or half black.

31:02.235 --> 31:04.778
It's just one... one love.

31:04.946 --> 31:08.448
♪ One love, one heart ♪

31:08.616 --> 31:13.078
♪ Let's join together
and l'll feel all right ♪

31:13.246 --> 31:16.582
- ♪ One love, one heart ♪
- ♪ O Lord, have mercy ♪

31:16.749 --> 31:20.586
♪ Let's join together
and l will feel all right... ♪

31:20.753 --> 31:24.256
Reporter: Undaunted by the driving rain,
a sea of faces awaited

31:24.424 --> 31:27.259
at the Palisadoes Airport
the arrival of a living legend.

31:27.427 --> 31:30.012
For some,
he was the King of Kings,

31:30.179 --> 31:32.890
the Lion of Judah...
even a god.

31:33.057 --> 31:35.475
Members of a local cult,
the Rastafarians,

31:35.643 --> 31:37.436
who worship this figure
as a deity,

31:37.604 --> 31:39.897
were present in full force.

31:43.651 --> 31:46.278
His lmperial Majesty,
Haile Selassie l,

31:46.446 --> 31:48.780
Emperor of Ethiopia, arrived.

31:48.948 --> 31:50.949
Edward Seaga:
When the plane landed,

31:51.117 --> 31:53.660
thousands ran out
and surrounded the plane,

31:53.828 --> 31:55.871
some of them smoking.

31:56.039 --> 31:57.623
Our police were powerless.

31:57.790 --> 32:00.792
And Selassie came to the door
of the plane, l remember,

32:00.960 --> 32:03.962
and after about 20 minutes...
and he just looked

32:04.130 --> 32:05.839
and he went back in.
( chuckles )

32:06.007 --> 32:08.967
It took a long time
to get him off the plane.

32:09.135 --> 32:12.429
Rita: So he came off the plane
and he greet.

32:12.597 --> 32:15.307
And l say... l say, "Wait,
but this is a little man."

32:15.475 --> 32:17.184
There is this little man
they say is God.

32:17.352 --> 32:19.394
"Them crazy."

32:19.562 --> 32:23.190
Patterson: l sit there on my bicycle,
waiting on him.

32:23.358 --> 32:25.984
And when him come up,
he look right in my face.

32:26.152 --> 32:29.696
It was like him look
into everybody face,

32:29.864 --> 32:32.783
but he look upon everyone.

32:32.951 --> 32:34.493
I remember l see that.

32:34.661 --> 32:37.204
Rita:
And he just turn his head around

32:37.372 --> 32:39.414
and he was looking
straight at me.

32:39.582 --> 32:42.084
And he did like this.

32:42.251 --> 32:44.670
Then l look and l look,
and l saw his hand,

32:44.837 --> 32:47.839
and l saw a mark on his hand.

32:48.007 --> 32:50.467
And believe me, my brother,

32:50.635 --> 32:52.761
when l saw that, l went crazy.

32:52.929 --> 32:55.555
I run all the way back
to Trench Town.

32:55.723 --> 32:59.476
♪ Take your troubles ♪

32:59.644 --> 33:04.606
♪ To Selassie... ♪

33:04.774 --> 33:09.027
( Women vocalizing )

33:13.408 --> 33:19.329
♪ He is the only
King of Kings ♪

33:20.331 --> 33:24.376
♪ He's the King of Kings ♪

33:24.544 --> 33:31.008
♪ King of Kings, Selassie ♪

33:31.175 --> 33:33.385
Chin:
The deeper Bob got into the faith,

33:33.553 --> 33:35.220
the Rastafarian faith,

33:35.388 --> 33:39.725
the more his music
became entwined.

33:41.352 --> 33:45.063
He was very into the social
commentary side of the music.

33:45.231 --> 33:48.442
Mr. Dodd didn't like that because it
wasn't commercial enough.

33:48.609 --> 33:50.235
So he was a little frustrated

33:50.403 --> 33:51.737
because he couldn't
do the music

33:51.904 --> 33:54.072
the way he really
wanted it to be done.

33:54.240 --> 33:59.244
Livingston: And also at that time,
money was a problem.

33:59.412 --> 34:03.957
Coxsone wasn't the kind of person
at the time to argue money with,

34:04.125 --> 34:06.293
unless you were willing
to go to war.

34:06.461 --> 34:09.295
McDonald: When you go and ask
him for your money,

34:09.464 --> 34:12.466
he usually like to bring off
some bad boy style

34:12.632 --> 34:14.926
'cause he has his thugs
around him.

34:15.094 --> 34:17.929
You know what l mean?
Enforcer type of guys.

34:18.097 --> 34:20.639
Lt was traditional
in those days

34:20.808 --> 34:24.811
that artists who recorded
never made money

34:24.978 --> 34:27.813
because the record company
who collected the money

34:27.982 --> 34:29.608
never gave the artist
any money.

34:29.775 --> 34:31.777
Yeah, we got paid
like minimum wage.

34:31.944 --> 34:35.280
Three pounds a week,
that's it, each.

34:35.447 --> 34:36.947
You couldn't live off it.

34:37.116 --> 34:39.326
- Interviewer: Could Bob live off it?
- Nah, man.

34:39.494 --> 34:42.829
That's why Bob had to leave
and start doing his own thing.

34:42.996 --> 34:46.792
Livingston: So Robert left the group
to go to Delaware,

34:46.958 --> 34:50.253
to the United States,
to migrate.

34:52.547 --> 34:55.967
( Sibley speaking )

34:59.806 --> 35:02.682
♪ Gotta hold on to
this feeling we got ♪

35:02.850 --> 35:05.143
♪ We gonna blow, blow, blow ♪

35:05.311 --> 35:08.313
♪ 'Cause we love, love,
love you now... ♪

35:08.481 --> 35:13.151
Yeah, well, that was a marriage
that l wasn't invited to, nor Peter.

35:13.319 --> 35:16.571
But because he's our brother,
we lived with it.

35:18.616 --> 35:20.867
Rita:
We got married, like, on the 11th,

35:21.035 --> 35:23.995
and he left on
the 12th of February.

35:24.163 --> 35:25.831
♪ Na na na na na ♪

35:25.998 --> 35:30.377
♪ Na na na na ♪

35:30.545 --> 35:35.090
♪ Run for cover ♪

35:35.258 --> 35:38.260
- ♪ Rain is taking over... ♪
- ( Barking )

35:38.427 --> 35:41.096
♪ Taking over... ♪

35:41.264 --> 35:43.223
Woman: He came here...
his mother wants him here.

35:43.391 --> 35:46.518
Bob loved his mother.

35:46.686 --> 35:50.730
Rita: He got a job at the du Pont Hotel
vacuuming the floor.

35:50.898 --> 35:53.525
Then he got a job at Chrysler.

35:53.693 --> 35:56.403
When he was working there,
he used to...

35:56.571 --> 35:59.698
l think he used to drive
one of the forklift.

35:59.866 --> 36:02.033
I think he have a song
out of that...

36:02.201 --> 36:04.536
driving the forklift all night.

36:04.704 --> 36:07.330
♪ I'm working all night ♪

36:07.498 --> 36:09.875
♪ Got to be all right ♪

36:10.042 --> 36:12.961
♪ See, l work for my bread ♪

36:13.129 --> 36:14.796
♪ All right ♪

36:14.964 --> 36:16.715
- ♪ Night and day ♪
- ♪ AII night ♪

36:16.883 --> 36:18.383
♪ Work for my pay ♪

36:18.551 --> 36:21.761
- ♪ AII right ♪
- ♪ Night and day ♪

36:21.929 --> 36:30.729
♪ No, no, no, no, no, no ♪

36:30.897 --> 36:34.107
- ♪ Can you feel it? ♪
- ♪ No, no, no, no, no, no... ♪

36:34.275 --> 36:36.693
Well, he was just
very humble, very loving,

36:36.861 --> 36:39.738
and he was very quiet, really.

36:39.906 --> 36:41.740
Interviewer: Was he smoking
a lot of ganja then?

36:41.908 --> 36:45.410
Ibis Pitts: Yeah, he was growing it,
too, man, in his backyard.

36:45.578 --> 36:48.580
And he had a row
of herb plants,

36:48.748 --> 36:51.666
l mean towering in the air,
and l couldn't believe it.

36:51.834 --> 36:54.294
'Cause at that time
in Wilmington, Delaware, man,

36:54.462 --> 36:58.048
they were kicking
people's doors in for a little joint.

36:58.216 --> 37:00.091
I used to go up to his house
and we'd go in the basement.

37:00.259 --> 37:03.470
He'd play his guitar and l would play
my congas. I played congas.

37:03.638 --> 37:04.804
And we would just jam.

37:04.972 --> 37:06.973
And l didn't really realize he was such
a great musician.

37:09.060 --> 37:11.061
Rita:
But he never gave up music,

37:11.229 --> 37:13.897
'cause his mommy,
she would write me to say,

37:14.065 --> 37:17.317
"All Nesta does
is stay in the basement

37:17.485 --> 37:19.444
and play his guitar."

37:20.613 --> 37:21.947
Bob: Well, l couldn't stand it

37:22.114 --> 37:24.491
because l wasn't doing
what I wanted to do.

37:24.659 --> 37:27.702
So I went back to Jamaica,
where l must get more freedom.

37:27.870 --> 37:30.538
♪ Bend down low ♪

37:32.083 --> 37:35.460
♪ Let me tell you
what l know, yeah ♪

37:37.296 --> 37:39.881
♪ Bend down low... ♪

37:42.510 --> 37:44.761
Livingston: When Robbie came back
from the US,

37:44.929 --> 37:48.640
we decided to start
our own independent label:

37:48.808 --> 37:50.475
"Wail'n Soul I'm."

37:50.643 --> 37:54.813
So we went in and did
"Bend Down Low."

37:54.981 --> 37:57.148
"Bend Down Low"
was a number one.

37:57.316 --> 37:59.943
We started to build
our own economy.

38:00.111 --> 38:03.822
We used to ride with our bicycles
and distribute the records to jukeboxes,

38:03.990 --> 38:07.701
sound systems, record stores,
with our bicycles.

38:07.868 --> 38:10.537
The Wailers' music
